WHAT HIGH VALYRIAN SCRIPT COULD BE LIKE
First, let us translate the famous inscription on the legendary horn Dragonbinder (A Dance with
Dragons, Chapter 63, Victarion I) into High Valyrian.
1. Logograms: ideas represented as pictures. A picture of a dragon means a dragon, and so on.
2. Phonetic complements: glyphs that give a hint that part of the word sounds a bit like the word
3. Determinatives: hints about what group of things does this word belong to. The glyph of water
tells that this is related to liquids.
High Valyrian is described as being written using glyphs. Let us assume that this means a writing
system a bit like that of Old Sumer or Egypt. This kind of writing system is called a logography, and
it contains three kinds of writing characters.
Here is the text written using this kind of writing system. I have marked the type of each
character in the transciption using CAPITAL letters.
